Exploring Match Percent Across the US¶

With enough data, it becomes possible to look the variation in matches across the US. Clearly there are cultural differences across the US, and as I explored way to model the data, it became clear that adding in controls for location was critical.

Example: I wanted to explore whether users who mentioned lip balm in the text of their profile were higher or lower matches with me than those who didn't. An initial logistic model, which predicted the presence of keywords related to lip balm with match percent, gender and sexual orientation controls, diet preferences, and fitness level, indicated that people who used lip balm had a significatly lower than average match with me. However, the addition of a control for the state the user reided in removed the effect completly, suggesting instead that the mention of lip balm may be more a proxy for geographic region (matches are higher on the coasts than they are in the dry central and southern states) than it was for any latent behavioral tedendency. Further exploration of the data supported this hypothesis, and prompted a deeper dive into the effects of region on my matches.

To explore the distributiuon of match percent, I started with choropleth maps of the US.

import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import plotly.plotly as py
import plotly.figure_factory as ff
from plotly.offline import init_notebook_mode, iplot
import colorlover as cl

init_notebook_mode(connected=True)

Loading Data¶

Data I scraped are in a sqlite database. I query the database using pandas--there is not need to use anything as complex as SQLAlchemy here--I just need a full pull of the user user data table and I need it in a tabular format.

The city_fips_link.csv file contains data that allows me to link a city and state in the form City, StateAvbbrv (e.g. Davis, CA) to a state and county FIPS code, required for many of the easy to use choropleth plotting packages. This data is a combination of data pulled from the zipcode R package and US census public data. More advanced plotting systems require linking data to shapefiles and I don't need that level of control here, plus I'm not going to plot oustide the US or at a level of detail other than than county or state, so using FIPS codes is approporiate.

In [2]:
fips_link_file = 'data/city_fips_link.csv'

db = 'sqlite:///data/userdata.db'

sql = """
SELECT username, 
  match_pct, 
  enemy_pct, 
  location, 
  city, 
  state 
FROM tbl_userdata
"""

df = pd.read_sql(sql=sql, con=db,index_col='username')
fips = pd.read_csv(fips_link_file, index_col=['state', 'city'], dtype={'COUNTY': str})

df = df.merge(right=fips[['COUNTY']], 
              how='inner',
              on=['state', 'city'])
df.rename(columns={'COUNTY':'fips_code'}, inplace=True)

Plotting Data¶

State-level data¶

I want to start by plotting state-level data scross the country. To do this, I need just the data aggregated by state abbreviation. The API for county-level choropleth and state-level is a little different.

In [3]:
# gaggregate to state level
state_level_agg = df.groupby('state')['match_pct'].agg(['mean', 'count', 'std']).reset_index()
state_level_agg['se'] = state_level_agg['std'] / state_level_agg['count'].pow(.5)

# create hover text
state_level_agg['text1'] = "Std dev: " + state_level_agg['std'].round(2).astype(str)  + '<br>' +\
    "Count: " + state_level_agg['count'].astype(str)
# create hover text
state_level_agg['text2'] = "Mean: " + state_level_agg['mean'].round(2).astype(str)  + '<br>' +\
    "Count: " + state_level_agg['count'].astype(str)
# create hover text
state_level_agg['text3'] = "Mean: " + state_level_agg['mean'].round(2).astype(str)  + '<br>' +\
    "Std dev: " + state_level_agg['std'].astype(str)
In [4]:
bg = 'rgb({v},{v},{v})'.format(v=255)
colorscale = cl.scales['6']['seq']['BuPu']

# state color scale needs a different format than county level will
state_colorscale = [[x.round(1),c] for x,c in zip(np.linspace(0,1,6), colorscale)]

def plot_state(data, locations, zvar, textvar, legend_title, main_title):
    data_state = [ dict(
        type='choropleth',
        colorscale=state_colorscale,
        autocolorscale=False,
        locations=state_level_agg[locations],
        z=state_level_agg[zvar].round(2),
        locationmode='USA-states',
        text=state_level_agg[textvar],
        marker = dict(
                line = dict (
                    color = bg,
                    width = 2
                ) ),
            colorbar = dict(
                title = legend_title)
        ) ]
    layout_state = dict(
    title = main_title,
        geo = dict(
            scope='usa',
            projection=dict( type='albers usa' ),
            showlakes = True,
            lakecolor = bg),
    )
    return dict(data=data_state, layout=layout_state)

fig1 = plot_state(state_level_agg, 
                  locations = 'state',
                  zvar='mean',
                 textvar='text1',
                 legend_title = 'Mean Match Percent',
                 main_title='National Match Percent by State')

fig2 = plot_state(state_level_agg, 
                  locations = 'state',
                  zvar='std',
                 textvar='text2',
                 legend_title = 'Standard Deviation of Match Percent',
                 main_title='National Match Standard Deviation by State')

fig3 = plot_state(state_level_agg, 
                  locations = 'state',
                  zvar='count',
                 textvar='text1',
                 legend_title = 'Mean Match Percent',
                 main_title='Count of Profiles Collected by State')
fig4 = plot_state(state_level_agg, 
                  locations = 'state',
                  zvar='se',
                 textvar='text1',
                 legend_title = 'Match Percent Standard Error',
                 main_title='National Match Standard Error by State')

First looking at the mean match percent, we see higher matches on coasts and in the further left-leaning states, lower matches in the south and midwest. A trend I expected.

In [5]:
iplot(fig1)

But this doesn't tell the whole story. If we look at the variance in match percent broken down by state, we see a that those same states I had low average matches with also have higher variance in match. The data are heteroskedastic, and thus, the mean is not an informative measure of central tendency. This also suggests that just using the state as a control in future analyses may not be sufficient. Note that a simple standard error (stdev/sqrt(n)), shows a great deal of consistency across states, reinforcing that this isn't just a sample size issue.

In [6]:
iplot(fig2)
iplot(fig4)

If we take a look at sample sizes of each state, we'll see that there are some drastic differences in California, Texas, and New York, but the rest of the states are all pretty consistent. This brings up the fact that my sampling methodology is likely biased and all results should be interpreted with caution.

In [7]:
iplot(fig3)

County-level Data¶

Since the data are fairly heteroskedastic, further breaking down the data by county may prove to be useful. States are large and diverse, and using state as a control may only be useful in the more homogenous states.

In [8]:
county_level_agg = df.groupby(['fips_code', 'state'])['match_pct'].agg(['mean', 'count', 'std']).reset_index()

# counties with only one value get NaN
#county_level_agg['std'].fillna(value=100, inplace=True)
county_level_agg['se'] = county_level_agg['std'] / county_level_agg['count'].pow(.5)

We can use plotly's user-friendly create_choropleth class, which allows for easier plotting of county-level data.

In [9]:
fig_n = ff.create_choropleth(
    fips=county_level_agg['fips_code'].tolist(),
    values=county_level_agg['count'].round(2).tolist(),
   # scope=scope,
    colorscale=colorscale,
    county_outline={'color': 'rgb(255,255,255)', 'width': 0.5},
    plot_bgcolor=bg,
    paper_bgcolor=bg,
   binning_endpoints=np.linspace(county_level_agg['count'].min(),
                                 county_level_agg['count'].max(),5).tolist(),
    legend_title="Sample Size",
    title='County-level Sample Size',
    show_state_data=True,
    round_legend_values=True,
)
fig_sd = ff.create_choropleth(
    fips=county_level_agg['fips_code'].tolist(),
    values=county_level_agg['std'].round(2).tolist(),
   # scope=scope,
    colorscale=colorscale,
    county_outline={'color': 'rgb(255,255,255)', 'width': 0.5},
    plot_bgcolor=bg,
    paper_bgcolor=bg,
   binning_endpoints=np.linspace(county_level_agg['std'].min(),
                                 county_level_agg['std'].max(),5).tolist(),
    legend_title="Standard Deviation",
    title='County-level Standard Deviation of Match Percent',
    show_state_data=True,
    round_legend_values=True,
)

If we look at the breakdown of either n or standard deviation by county, we see small concentrations of high n counties and high SD counties (these are often the same, but counties with n=1 getting NaN, and thus sorted first in the standard deviation choropleth map), surrounded by numerous counties of low N and many with no data at all.

In [10]:
iplot(fig_n)
iplot(fig_sd)

Notice that New York County has almost 2.5 million records, but of the 59 counties I have data from in New York State, 34 of them have less than 50 records, and only 12 have more than 1000 records. This trend is seen across states, with a few counties making of the vast majority of data I've collected. Further exploration into county and state population levels would be useful in determining how biased my sample is, but ultimatly, the data will never be able to generalize beyond what I've collected. It is impossible to tell if my sample is representative of users of this dataing site as a whole, and dating site users themselves are a highly biased sample of the poulation. Luckily, I only started this project to have a little fun--I did it to learn more about web scraping and new data analysis methods, not to learn about the dating pool.
